1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:06,850 --> 00:00:08,020
Hey bro, I'm not late.

3
00:00:08,350 --> 00:00:12,450
I was here this morning already, just popped out for a little something to go with the beer.

4
00:00:12,520 --> 00:00:13,260
What's that?

5
00:00:14,550 --> 00:00:15,650
Is that some kind of panel?

6
00:00:16,350 --> 00:00:18,850
It's a new security system, Mr. Ozzak.

7
00:00:19,150 --> 00:00:20,250
For the insurance.

8
00:00:20,850 --> 00:00:25,150
Bro, didn't you say you don't want any technology in the store?

9
00:00:25,350 --> 00:00:28,250
I said I don't want any techno in the store.

10
00:00:28,950 --> 00:00:31,250
This is your code, memorize it.

11
00:00:32,050 --> 00:00:33,650
I'll never remember that in my life.

12
00:00:34,450 --> 00:00:38,540
Mr. Ozzak, what's so hard about 847-24869?

13
00:00:38,540 --> 00:00:40,140
It's making my head spin.

14
00:00:40,260 --> 00:00:40,680
Bimbo!

15
00:00:41,200 --> 00:00:44,690
It went off again.

16
00:00:44,690 --> 00:00:48,150
The nice man said it's a very sensitive device.

17
00:00:50,450 --> 00:00:50,950
Ozzak, leave it!

18
00:00:54,570 --> 00:00:56,510
Watch, punch in that code!

19
00:00:56,690 --> 00:00:57,330
You hear me?

20
00:00:57,750 --> 00:00:58,390
Ozzak!

21
00:00:58,990 --> 00:00:59,630
You hear me?

22
00:00:59,950 --> 00:01:00,590
Ozzak!

23
00:01:01,850 --> 00:01:04,310
Marcelka, turn off the alarm, quick!

24
00:01:07,950 --> 00:01:08,450
What happened?

25
00:01:11,250 --> 00:01:12,340
Are you alright?

26
00:01:13,550 --> 00:01:14,050
I had a terrible urge to lick my paws.

27
00:01:16,630 --> 00:01:18,850
Stop, or else.

28
00:01:19,450 --> 00:01:22,770
Wait, that alarm sounds like a school bell.

29
00:01:22,950 --> 00:01:25,930
Of course, Ozzak went through a phase where he was terrified of school.

30
00:01:25,930 --> 00:01:27,990
No, school is a disguised prison.

31
00:01:28,090 --> 00:01:31,170
When he heard the bell, he'd start barking and the teacher would throw him out of class.

32
00:01:31,250 --> 00:01:35,970
He got the same note 250 times: hits and barks when I arrive.

33
00:01:36,250 --> 00:01:40,050
Right, but what are we going to do about our alarm?

34
00:01:40,150 --> 00:01:42,350
Nothing, Ozzak has to learn the code.

35
00:02:14,050 --> 00:02:17,950
Yeah, you look like a model in this one again, while I look like a potato.

36
00:02:18,050 --> 00:02:19,850
Stop it, please.

37
00:02:21,150 --> 00:02:22,480
It's probably the photographer.

38
00:02:22,850 --> 00:02:24,850
Maybe he only photographs vegetables.

39
00:02:27,650 --> 00:02:28,170
Hey, girls.

40
00:02:28,370 --> 00:02:28,770
Hey.

41
00:02:29,250 --> 00:02:30,390
Hi, girls.

42
00:02:30,850 --> 00:02:32,450
But you look healthy here.

43
00:02:33,350 --> 00:02:35,050
Kind of like a sprout.

44
00:02:35,450 --> 00:02:38,100
Iva, my passport photo is going to be ugly.

45
00:02:38,450 --> 00:02:40,350
You should see Ozzak's ID card.

46
00:02:40,550 --> 00:02:43,140
He's eleven in it and had to draw in the hair and beard.

47
00:02:43,140 --> 00:02:44,420
Think that would help?

48
00:02:45,250 --> 00:02:48,050
Just don't use a green marker like Ozzak did.

49
00:02:50,250 --> 00:02:51,650
Why were you getting photos taken anyway?

50
00:02:52,250 --> 00:02:53,050
For a passport.

51
00:02:53,850 --> 00:02:54,850
Are you going somewhere?

52
00:02:54,940 --> 00:02:56,220
No, but where would we want to go?

53
00:02:56,220 --> 00:02:58,450
Well, I'd have to let you go first.

54
00:02:58,540 --> 00:03:00,180
And you wouldn't let me?

55
00:03:00,540 --> 00:03:02,280
I would, but you'd have to ask.

56
00:03:02,950 --> 00:03:06,450
See, like to Paris, to Montmartre, to see Amelie.

57
00:03:07,050 --> 00:03:09,750
Who's Amelie and why are you going to Paris to see her?

58
00:03:10,650 --> 00:03:12,860
Actually, Sasa found a great DVD rental place.

59
00:03:12,860 --> 00:03:13,520
In Paris?

60
00:03:14,950 --> 00:03:16,150
No, around the corner.

61
00:03:17,050 --> 00:03:18,990
Dad, Amelie from Montmartre is a movie.

62
00:03:19,450 --> 00:03:21,110
And why do you need a passport?

63
00:03:21,250 --> 00:03:24,550
I need two documents with photos so they can make us an ID card.

64
00:03:25,850 --> 00:03:32,560
Ivuska, a DVD rental around the corner, that's the dumbest excuse I've ever heard.

65
00:03:32,560 --> 00:03:34,760
But it's true, Mr. Pacovsky, it opened yesterday.

66
00:03:34,920 --> 00:03:36,620
Yeah, and they have a tea room there too.

67
00:03:37,150 --> 00:03:40,950
Right, a tea room, in a newly opened DVD rental.

68
00:03:42,050 --> 00:03:43,050
Is that the bell?

69
00:03:47,550 --> 00:03:48,950
You have a dog?

70
00:03:53,550 --> 00:03:56,750
That must be the new dogs from the army.

71
00:04:00,720 --> 00:04:02,200
Your dog is in the army?

72
00:04:11,350 --> 00:04:13,750
Paris International?

73
00:04:14,150 --> 00:04:15,470
A modeling agency.

74
00:04:15,470 --> 00:04:15,990
What?

75
00:04:16,950 --> 00:04:19,370
Iva got a letter from a modeling agency?

76
00:04:19,370 --> 00:04:21,150
Isn't she a bit too young?

77
00:04:21,350 --> 00:04:22,590
On the contrary, it's high time.

78
00:04:25,250 --> 00:04:25,850
Hi.

79
00:04:26,930 --> 00:04:27,690
Hey.

80
00:04:27,990 --> 00:04:28,750
Hi.

81
00:04:31,450 --> 00:04:32,850
Paris International.

82
00:04:33,150 --> 00:04:34,850
A modeling agency.

83
00:04:39,450 --> 00:04:43,950
Dear applicant, the committee has accepted your application for the international modeling course.

84
00:04:44,550 --> 00:04:47,780
Wait, this must be a mistake, I didn't send anything to any agency.

85
00:04:48,950 --> 00:04:50,050
Read on.

86
00:04:50,870 --> 00:04:55,010
Send your photograph on a theme of your choice and include a short resume.

87
00:04:55,110 --> 00:04:59,070
If you advance to the next round, you will participate in a week-long internship in Paris.

88
00:05:00,350 --> 00:05:02,450
Someone's been messing with me again, right?

89
00:05:03,150 --> 00:05:04,850
You think I won't figure it out?

90
00:05:05,050 --> 00:05:08,050
First a passport, then a letter from Paris.

91
00:05:08,850 --> 00:05:10,550
I don't know anything about this letter.

92
00:05:10,750 --> 00:05:11,310
You don't?

93
00:05:11,650 --> 00:05:15,950
In that case you probably won't mind if I forbid it.

94
00:05:20,650 --> 00:05:24,290
Tomas, don't be so hard on her, this is great news for her.

95
00:05:24,290 --> 00:05:26,290
What's so great about my daughter wanting to do modeling?

96
00:05:27,170 --> 00:05:27,550
Modeling?

97
00:05:28,210 --> 00:05:29,770
That's fantastic!

98
00:05:30,070 --> 00:05:31,330
I knew she was cut out for it.

99
00:05:31,470 --> 00:05:31,950
And you?

100
00:05:32,110 --> 00:05:33,550
I saw it ages ago.

101
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:37,340
Too bad you didn't think of it sooner, we could've started at six.

102
00:05:37,520 --> 00:05:39,240
Ozzak, I don't know, isn't it a bit early?

103
00:05:39,360 --> 00:05:40,200
What do you know about it?

104
00:05:40,340 --> 00:05:42,500
My buddy Pecka started with his kid at four.

105
00:05:42,620 --> 00:05:44,260
Ivuska, do you even have any pumps?

106
00:05:45,350 --> 00:05:48,000
Pumps, pumps are for little boys.

107
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:48,840
I'll be right back.

108
00:05:49,820 --> 00:05:50,240
Pumps.

109
00:05:52,510 --> 00:05:53,270
Typical Ozzak.

110
00:05:53,390 --> 00:05:55,450
He knows nothing about modeling but has an opinion.

111
00:05:55,650 --> 00:05:58,190
When the only expert from practice here is me.

112
00:05:58,510 --> 00:05:59,450
You were a model?

113
00:05:59,550 --> 00:05:59,670
Yeah.

114
00:05:59,810 --> 00:06:04,510
I was Miss Tangerine of the Fruit and Vegetables company, 1982-83.

115
00:06:04,730 --> 00:06:06,170
Wait, I'll show you a photo.

116
00:06:06,350 --> 00:06:07,770
Aren't you a bit short for a model?

117
00:06:08,010 --> 00:06:09,430
That didn't matter back then at all.

118
00:06:09,570 --> 00:06:10,910
I was a huge success.

119
00:06:11,010 --> 00:06:13,950
Wherever tangerines appeared, there was an enormous line.

120
00:06:14,620 --> 00:06:16,440
Ivuska, I thought you had some sense.

121
00:06:16,580 --> 00:06:18,480
You have no idea what awaits you out there.

122
00:06:18,680 --> 00:06:20,960
Geez, Dad, I don't know anything about this letter, I swear.

123
00:06:21,040 --> 00:06:25,380
Right now you have no idea what the job involves and you have nothing to start with.

124
00:06:25,560 --> 00:06:26,760
Worst case, I'll break open my piggy bank.

125
00:06:27,100 --> 00:06:28,140
Look, that's me.

126
00:06:28,950 --> 00:06:31,350
You're simply too short and too old for a model.

127
00:06:32,020 --> 00:06:32,460
Tomas?

128
00:06:33,400 --> 00:06:34,340
Are we on first-name terms?

129
00:06:34,580 --> 00:06:35,940
No, that wasn't meant for you.

130
00:06:36,500 --> 00:06:37,740
Nice, orange.

131
00:06:38,450 --> 00:06:41,450
Now among those twelve-year-old beanpoles you don't stand a chance.

132
00:06:41,850 --> 00:06:43,750
Dad, that's really mean right now.

133
00:06:43,880 --> 00:06:45,500
Would you really forbid it?

134
00:06:45,600 --> 00:06:47,460
I wouldn't forbid it, I am forbidding it.

135
00:06:47,520 --> 00:06:48,820
But you have no right.

136
00:06:49,040 --> 00:06:49,320
I do.

137
00:06:49,740 --> 00:06:51,860
You definitely need parental consent and I'll...

138
00:06:52,440 --> 00:06:52,720
Not give it!

139
00:06:56,750 --> 00:06:57,450
Tomas, don't be so hard on her, it's pointless.

140
00:06:59,470 --> 00:07:00,950
My father forbade it too.

141
00:07:01,090 --> 00:07:02,430
He was a wise man.

142
00:07:02,570 --> 00:07:04,030
I haven't spoken to him since.

143
00:07:04,490 --> 00:07:06,250
Modeling is a profession like any other.

144
00:07:06,470 --> 00:07:08,770
Modeling is a front for human trafficking.

145
00:07:09,170 --> 00:07:11,050
Tomas, you really know nothing about it, do you?

146
00:07:11,950 --> 00:07:13,550
She's not going, and that's final.

147
00:07:13,750 --> 00:07:15,650
Here, look at this.

148
00:07:17,350 --> 00:07:19,150
This is better than pumps.

149
00:07:24,450 --> 00:07:25,950
We need to let this settle.

150
00:07:28,350 --> 00:07:29,850
Dad's completely out of touch.

151
00:07:30,350 --> 00:07:35,050
Not only is he a hundred years behind, in his world apes are still swimming in the ocean calling themselves fish.

152
00:07:35,950 --> 00:07:38,070
And that letter was a pretty dumb idea too.

153
00:07:38,350 --> 00:07:41,050
It must have been Lexa, I'll kill him.

154
00:07:41,370 --> 00:07:42,370
It wasn't Lexa.

155
00:07:42,370 --> 00:07:45,790
Then who else, I don't just leave my photos lying around, do I?

156
00:07:46,050 --> 00:07:47,750
Well, sometimes you do.

157
00:07:49,610 --> 00:07:50,150
What is it?

158
00:07:50,930 --> 00:07:56,770
I was looking for a photo where I'd look good and couldn't find one, and yours was really pretty.

159
00:07:58,630 --> 00:08:01,770
And then I realized that sending it under my name would be fraud.

160
00:08:01,950 --> 00:08:03,630
So why did you want to be a model anyway?

161
00:08:04,090 --> 00:08:06,250
Everyone likes models and everyone notices them.

162
00:08:06,390 --> 00:08:07,610
They date football players.

163
00:08:10,550 --> 00:08:11,450
Do you like it?

164
00:08:12,250 --> 00:08:13,850
No, well, let's just take the letter, throw it away and forget about it.

165
00:08:17,610 --> 00:08:20,350
No wait, Iva, it'd be a shame, since we're already in the second round.

166
00:08:22,050 --> 00:08:23,300
We're in the second round?

167
00:08:23,450 --> 00:08:25,840
The trip is for the model and her companion.

168
00:08:25,840 --> 00:08:27,170
So what?

169
00:08:31,750 --> 00:08:35,580
Well, if an expert committee selected me.

170
00:08:35,850 --> 00:08:37,150
Iva, you're amazing.

171
00:08:37,350 --> 00:08:39,250
Yeah, but the deadline is in a few days.

172
00:08:39,650 --> 00:08:42,550
Don't worry, I'll write your resume and I've already got a photographer.

173
00:08:43,160 --> 00:08:44,200
We're going to Paris.

174
00:08:50,850 --> 00:08:53,050
Does it say anywhere why it keeps going off on its own?

175
00:08:53,070 --> 00:08:53,530
No.

176
00:08:54,350 --> 00:08:56,790
But I found a short story in Croatian in here.

177
00:08:56,790 --> 00:08:58,350
Well, that probably won't help us, will it?

178
00:08:59,850 --> 00:09:03,360
The main thing is we need to figure out how Mr. Ozzak can remember the code.

179
00:09:03,360 --> 00:09:05,020
That won't be in the manual.

180
00:09:05,550 --> 00:09:09,550
Bro, I was just thinking it'd be best if I didn't come here as long as this thing's here.

181
00:09:09,670 --> 00:09:11,170
It's going to be here forever.

182
00:09:11,210 --> 00:09:13,470
Ozzak, you can't skip out of here like you did school.

183
00:09:13,570 --> 00:09:14,270
You work here.

184
00:09:14,410 --> 00:09:15,810
You're not going to leave me at its mercy.

185
00:09:16,110 --> 00:09:17,730
Mr. Ozzak can't be here alone.

186
00:09:17,770 --> 00:09:19,050
What if he bites someone?

187
00:09:19,230 --> 00:09:22,770
What's so hard about remembering one stupid number?

188
00:09:22,890 --> 00:09:23,290
Look.

189
00:09:30,050 --> 00:09:33,050
Marcelka, is there something in the manual about changing the code?

190
00:09:33,280 --> 00:09:33,800
Wait.

191
00:09:34,800 --> 00:09:35,500
Here it is.

192
00:09:35,950 --> 00:09:38,850
Press the asterisk for seven seconds.

193
00:09:39,960 --> 00:09:41,380
I want eight ones.

194
00:09:41,460 --> 00:09:42,820
You should be able to remember that.

195
00:09:42,960 --> 00:09:44,020
I'm not good at this.

196
00:09:44,320 --> 00:09:45,800
I'll panic and punch in eight twos.

197
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:47,280
Hold on, bro, listen.

198
00:09:55,150 --> 00:09:57,750
It fits and that's it, it has to work.

199
00:09:57,750 --> 00:09:58,790
Let's try it, come on.

200
00:10:03,760 --> 00:10:04,900
Great, keypad.

201
00:10:04,960 --> 00:10:05,700
And done.

202
00:10:06,140 --> 00:10:08,040
But nothing about melodies in here.

203
00:10:08,220 --> 00:10:09,320
This remembers itself.

204
00:10:09,600 --> 00:10:14,160
But it's proven that memory retains important dates better, like a birthday.

205
00:10:14,320 --> 00:10:16,040
Good lord, who remembers their birthday?

206
00:10:16,580 --> 00:10:20,800
For example, my code is the exact date and hour when Zoran got Czech citizenship.

207
00:10:32,250 --> 00:10:33,050
I have a clear vision.

208
00:10:34,450 --> 00:10:35,590
Beauty and the Beast.

209
00:10:35,590 --> 00:10:38,250
The contrast between beauty and danger is all the rage now.

210
00:10:38,650 --> 00:10:40,070
And how do you want to do that?

211
00:10:40,250 --> 00:10:45,250
I was thinking we'd go to the zoo and lock you in a cage with a tiger for a bit.

212
00:10:47,450 --> 00:10:48,950
What if something happens to me?

213
00:10:49,350 --> 00:10:50,750
I only need a few minutes.

214
00:10:51,350 --> 00:10:54,600
Lexa, the model is supposed to survive the shoot, did that occur to you?

215
00:10:54,850 --> 00:10:56,450
A tiger will rip my head off.

216
00:10:56,850 --> 00:10:58,150
Beauty has to hurt.

217
00:10:59,350 --> 00:11:01,310
I'm not getting into any cage.

218
00:11:01,750 --> 00:11:04,590
Then we'll take a tamer animal, a bunny, a kitten, or a pony.

219
00:11:04,590 --> 00:11:09,670
But a pony isn't bloodthirsty, we need something exciting, something dangerous, for the emotion.

220
00:11:09,930 --> 00:11:12,570
No tiger and no big cats, period.

221
00:11:12,690 --> 00:11:15,210
Right, Lexa, something obedient, so it doesn't rip Iva's head off.

222
00:11:22,950 --> 00:11:25,150
Iva, Mr. Ozzak isn't an animal.

223
00:11:34,450 --> 00:11:34,880
Hi!

224
00:11:34,880 --> 00:11:36,000
Hey, look what you're missing.

225
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:38,650
Those exhaust pipes are actually chrome.

226
00:11:41,160 --> 00:11:43,460
We need to photograph Iva with some animal, are you in?

227
00:11:43,760 --> 00:11:44,880
Sure, no problem.

228
00:11:45,040 --> 00:11:47,760
I knew you wouldn't pass up this chance, Ivuska.

229
00:11:48,350 --> 00:11:49,990
But don't tell Dad about it.

230
00:11:50,130 --> 00:11:51,070
I can't lie to him.

231
00:11:51,550 --> 00:11:53,750
But you don't have to tell him either.

232
00:11:54,350 --> 00:11:56,550
I'll be unreadable like Zoran's accounts.

233
00:11:57,750 --> 00:11:59,790
But hurry, that Harley won't glue itself together.

234
00:11:59,790 --> 00:12:01,110
So where's the animal I'm supposed to photograph?

235
00:12:01,550 --> 00:12:02,930
I'm the photographer.

236
00:12:02,930 --> 00:12:03,310
Oh.

237
00:12:03,310 --> 00:12:04,650
Fine, where's the animal?

238
00:12:04,950 --> 00:12:06,090
You have to make it.

239
00:12:06,350 --> 00:12:06,970
Out of what?

240
00:12:07,350 --> 00:12:08,710
You'll be the animal.

241
00:12:08,710 --> 00:12:09,090
Right.

242
00:12:10,050 --> 00:12:10,850
Me, an animal?

243
00:12:11,350 --> 00:12:12,950
I'm a human being.

244
00:12:12,950 --> 00:12:14,230
Or, or am I not?

245
00:12:14,970 --> 00:12:16,290
Is there a problem here?

246
00:12:16,370 --> 00:12:20,890
We want to photograph Iva with some dangerous creature, for the beauty and the beast contrast.

247
00:12:21,240 --> 00:12:23,400
Great idea, Lexa, that's trendy right now.

248
00:12:23,540 --> 00:12:29,160
According to research, an ad with an animal is the second most effective, right after full-frontal nudity.

249
00:12:30,750 --> 00:12:31,850
Full-frontal nudity?

250
00:12:32,350 --> 00:12:34,750
Like, completely?

251
00:12:35,440 --> 00:12:37,940
That's a hundred thousand percent better than an animal.

252
00:12:38,080 --> 00:12:39,080
Forget it.

253
00:12:39,100 --> 00:12:40,300
No changes to the plan, got it?

254
00:12:40,540 --> 00:12:40,820
Got it.

255
00:12:40,840 --> 00:12:41,580
Good for you, Iva.

256
00:12:41,640 --> 00:12:42,880
You have to stick to your principles.

257
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:45,920
They asked me too if I'd pose for a collection in the nude.

258
00:12:45,960 --> 00:12:46,640
I refused.

259
00:12:47,880 --> 00:12:50,840
But be careful, working with animals isn't a walk in the park either.

260
00:12:51,020 --> 00:12:54,080
During a fur coat shoot, a fox bit me once.

261
00:12:54,380 --> 00:12:56,220
Lucky it didn't have venomous teeth.

262
00:12:56,800 --> 00:12:59,120
I'm not an animal, I have an ID card now.

263
00:12:59,950 --> 00:13:03,140
No, no, you'll just play the dangerous animal, Ozzak, it's in you.

264
00:13:03,140 --> 00:13:04,220
Well, you do look dangerous.

265
00:13:05,550 --> 00:13:07,150
I really look dangerous, bimbo?

266
00:13:07,170 --> 00:13:08,290
You look like a bum.

267
00:13:09,950 --> 00:13:11,050
Well then, you're not just saying that?

268
00:13:11,050 --> 00:13:13,050
Trust me, you're a textbook vagabond.

269
00:13:15,450 --> 00:13:16,450
I always wanted to play villains.

270
00:13:16,650 --> 00:13:18,190
Winnetou and Superman, Grandma.

271
00:13:18,850 --> 00:13:20,550
Like how she threw kids over fences.

272
00:13:20,830 --> 00:13:21,790
Great.

273
00:13:22,850 --> 00:13:23,350
So we can shoot it right here.

274
00:13:23,350 --> 00:13:29,270
And we'll call the collection "Pretty Salesgirl Threatened by a Vagabond."

275
00:13:30,650 --> 00:13:31,550
No, I've got something better.

276
00:13:32,350 --> 00:13:34,950
"Vagabond Threatens Pretty Salesgirl."

277
00:13:36,150 --> 00:13:38,650
I don't know, won't that be too much fiction?

278
00:13:38,850 --> 00:13:39,650
Fiction?

279
00:13:39,950 --> 00:13:40,710
Ivuska?

280
00:13:41,250 --> 00:13:43,450
For me, that's everyday reality.

281
00:13:53,250 --> 00:13:55,450
Today's youth is such a bunch of wimps.

282
00:13:56,150 --> 00:13:59,380
I see, so that's why you're on your third glass.

283
00:13:59,750 --> 00:14:01,150
What did Iva do now?

284
00:14:01,450 --> 00:14:02,650
A whole country of fools.

285
00:14:03,550 --> 00:14:06,150
First, she gets passport photos taken.

286
00:14:06,550 --> 00:14:09,730
Second, she gets a letter from Paris to become a model.

287
00:14:10,850 --> 00:14:14,170
And third, she claims it's a mistake and thinks I won't figure it out.

288
00:14:14,170 --> 00:14:15,630
Be glad, please.

289
00:14:16,250 --> 00:14:18,310
Sasa would never enter a competition.

290
00:14:18,550 --> 00:14:20,750
And even if she did, they'd pick Iva anyway.

291
00:14:21,150 --> 00:14:23,730
Yeah, but she's got plans and she won't tell me.

292
00:14:23,950 --> 00:14:25,150
That's the thanks for everything.

293
00:14:25,450 --> 00:14:27,050
Maybe it really is a coincidence.

294
00:14:27,550 --> 00:14:30,490
She coincidentally needs a passport and coincidentally gets picked as a model.

295
00:14:30,490 --> 00:14:32,310
And coincidentally forgot to tell you.

296
00:14:32,790 --> 00:14:35,250
Too many coincidences at once, don't you think?

297
00:14:35,430 --> 00:14:36,010
Look, don't worry.

298
00:14:36,450 --> 00:14:38,550
You can't last in modeling forever anyway.

299
00:14:38,750 --> 00:14:41,610
Parties, cocaine, one-night stands, you get tired of it eventually.

300
00:14:45,450 --> 00:14:48,150
That's not exactly the best way to calm me down.

301
00:14:48,750 --> 00:14:49,550
Point taken.

302
00:14:50,050 --> 00:14:51,450
I've got something better for you.

303
00:14:57,350 --> 00:15:01,150
Now that might actually calm me down.

304
00:15:03,350 --> 00:15:08,850
So after the fifty-first, you need to look as menacing as possible, Mr. Ozzak.

305
00:15:09,400 --> 00:15:09,840
Grr!

306
00:15:09,840 --> 00:15:12,950
That would only scare a small child.

307
00:15:12,950 --> 00:15:15,450
Imagine you want to rob her.

308
00:15:15,580 --> 00:15:17,040
I don't want to rob anyone.

309
00:15:17,040 --> 00:15:19,040
Imagine you have to receive a shipment.

310
00:15:19,040 --> 00:15:20,720
Receiving shipments is your job, bimbo.

311
00:15:20,840 --> 00:15:21,760
That's it.

312
00:15:21,780 --> 00:15:23,040
Now try it on Iva.

313
00:15:24,550 --> 00:15:26,290
Receiving shipments is your job, Ivuska.

314
00:15:27,700 --> 00:15:30,120
Try threatening her with that machete.

315
00:15:30,380 --> 00:15:31,380
Cut open her neckline.

316
00:15:31,740 --> 00:15:33,820
Nobody's cutting any necklines.

317
00:15:34,450 --> 00:15:37,250
We've been shooting for three hours and don't have a single photo.

318
00:15:37,450 --> 00:15:41,350
Ozzak, imagine it's not Iva but someone from Moravanka.

319
00:15:42,070 --> 00:15:42,590
What?

320
00:15:43,250 --> 00:15:45,910
And did you know heavy metal came from disco?

321
00:15:46,050 --> 00:15:47,170
What are you talking about?

322
00:15:47,170 --> 00:15:47,670
It's true.

323
00:15:48,090 --> 00:15:49,490
And now it's going back to its roots.

324
00:15:49,510 --> 00:15:50,450
You're asking for it, bimbo?

325
00:15:50,670 --> 00:15:52,790
Led Zeppelin are touring with Tokio Hotel.

326
00:15:53,430 --> 00:15:55,390
Metallica is recording Britney Spears singles.

327
00:15:55,530 --> 00:15:57,870
Ozzy cut his hair and started dating Celine Dion.

328
00:15:59,090 --> 00:16:02,150
Lexa, Lexa, get it, go, get it, go.

329
00:16:03,550 --> 00:16:04,850
Lexa, Lexa.

330
00:16:08,060 --> 00:16:09,720
Lexa, you were supposed to photograph him.

331
00:16:15,650 --> 00:16:16,750
Wow, Iva's not even in it.

332
00:16:26,750 --> 00:16:28,150
What's going on here?

333
00:16:28,250 --> 00:16:30,450
Nothing, Mr. Pacovsky.

334
00:16:30,550 --> 00:16:31,660
Testing the alarm.

335
00:16:31,660 --> 00:16:32,900
Yeah, testing the alarm.

336
00:16:33,360 --> 00:16:35,160
We discovered it doesn't work properly.

337
00:16:35,640 --> 00:16:37,220
Well, we already know that.

338
00:16:37,750 --> 00:16:42,220
We wanted to change the ring to a siren, but that doesn't work either.

339
00:16:42,220 --> 00:16:43,480
We know that too.

340
00:16:43,480 --> 00:16:47,540
And now we're about to look inside.

341
00:16:47,540 --> 00:16:47,800
Right.

342
00:16:48,550 --> 00:16:50,150
And why does Lexa have a camera?

343
00:16:50,490 --> 00:16:52,290
For insurance documentation.

344
00:16:52,410 --> 00:16:54,230
So they don't think we're frauds.

345
00:16:56,750 --> 00:17:01,750
And why is Iva all dressed up?

346
00:17:02,550 --> 00:17:04,150
So she looks nice in the photos.

347
00:17:04,350 --> 00:17:05,030
Why would she need to?

348
00:17:05,430 --> 00:17:08,030
No, in case those insurance guys might be interested.

349
00:17:08,230 --> 00:17:09,810
They have very refined taste.

350
00:17:10,490 --> 00:17:15,450
Look, you think I can't tell you're photographing Iva for that competition?

351
00:17:15,730 --> 00:17:16,870
No way, no.

352
00:17:20,550 --> 00:17:23,650
You think I'm an idiot!

353
00:17:24,650 --> 00:17:27,450
Have you all completely lost your minds?

354
00:17:36,650 --> 00:17:53,650
Don't be mad at me anymore, Dad.

355
00:17:53,950 --> 00:17:56,600
The worst part is it all happened behind my back.

356
00:17:56,600 --> 00:17:58,400
But that's not my fault, it was Sasa.

357
00:17:58,560 --> 00:17:59,420
You always say that.

358
00:17:59,500 --> 00:18:01,280
No, I always say it was Lexa.

359
00:18:04,050 --> 00:18:06,550
And on top of everything, exploiting Ozzak.

360
00:18:07,450 --> 00:18:09,090
The photos are unusable anyway.

361
00:18:09,170 --> 00:18:11,090
In all of them his eyes are closed and he's cringing.

362
00:18:11,250 --> 00:18:12,630
That's because he's afraid of flashes.

363
00:18:13,130 --> 00:18:13,530
And?

364
00:18:13,770 --> 00:18:16,490
At eleven he got caught outside in a big thunderstorm.

365
00:18:17,550 --> 00:18:18,490
Alone in the mountains.

366
00:18:18,750 --> 00:18:20,350
And what does that have to do with photography?

367
00:18:21,050 --> 00:18:24,650
Since then, he flinches at the last second in every photo with a flash.

368
00:18:25,350 --> 00:18:27,110
How come I never noticed that?

369
00:18:27,550 --> 00:18:30,370
Do you remember us ever taking a photo together?

370
00:18:30,550 --> 00:18:31,550
Yeah, once.

371
00:18:31,850 --> 00:18:33,310
I'm turned with my back in it.

372
00:18:33,310 --> 00:18:35,350
Well, that was a faster reaction.

373
00:18:36,550 --> 00:18:37,450
That's terrible.

374
00:18:38,050 --> 00:18:41,650
I don't want to imagine what would happen if he saw a strobe light.

375
00:18:41,820 --> 00:18:42,780
Hey, hi.

376
00:18:42,780 --> 00:18:43,950
Hey.

377
00:18:44,050 --> 00:18:45,780
Hey, Lexa.

378
00:18:45,780 --> 00:18:46,500
So?

379
00:18:46,500 --> 00:18:49,400
We picked one and sent it right away.

380
00:18:49,400 --> 00:18:50,820
Mr. Ozzak is in the background.

381
00:18:50,920 --> 00:18:52,400
I'd call it rage.

382
00:18:52,400 --> 00:18:54,450
The central figure is Mr. Pacovsky.

383
00:18:54,540 --> 00:18:54,980
What?

384
00:18:54,980 --> 00:18:56,980
This is what you sent?

385
00:18:57,250 --> 00:18:59,350
We all look like idiots here.

386
00:18:59,750 --> 00:19:03,750
You sent my photo, are you crazy, what if I ended up in the tabloids?

387
00:19:03,800 --> 00:19:04,240
Let me see.

388
00:19:07,140 --> 00:19:07,860
Not bad.

389
00:19:09,100 --> 00:19:10,160
Rage, you say?

390
00:19:10,820 --> 00:19:12,680
I look pretty authoritative here.

391
00:19:12,900 --> 00:19:13,820
Well, definitely.

392
00:19:13,900 --> 00:19:15,680
Like a guy who doesn't take any nonsense.

393
00:19:16,750 --> 00:19:19,350
And look how terrified Ivuska looks.

394
00:19:19,440 --> 00:19:20,540
All thanks to you!

395
00:19:21,350 --> 00:19:23,350
And you've got instant respect, huh?

396
00:19:26,450 --> 00:19:28,580
And look at Mr. Ozzak.

397
00:19:29,050 --> 00:19:30,750
Yeah, he always looks like that.

398
00:19:42,250 --> 00:19:45,750
Dear applicant, your photograph caught our attention.

399
00:19:46,350 --> 00:19:47,650
What, so they picked you?

400
00:19:48,150 --> 00:19:50,750
Unfortunately, from the submitted information we determined you are too young and too old for modeling.

401
00:19:53,110 --> 00:19:54,470
How old?

402
00:19:55,150 --> 00:19:56,850
You're only sixteen.

403
00:19:58,850 --> 00:20:04,150
However, we would like contact information for the terrified bum and the puffy man in the photograph with you.

404
00:20:04,440 --> 00:20:05,780
That would be you?

405
00:20:08,650 --> 00:20:10,050
What do they want from us?

406
00:20:11,250 --> 00:20:16,250
An offer of lucrative collaboration from the company Schiele Auge, based in Geneva.

407
00:20:16,750 --> 00:20:17,190
Lucrative?

408
00:20:17,950 --> 00:20:19,050
Will it hurt?

409
00:20:19,450 --> 00:20:21,450
That means there'll be money, Uncle.

410
00:20:21,450 --> 00:20:22,750
Then what are we waiting for?

411
00:20:22,970 --> 00:20:24,230
Wait, what does the company do?

412
00:20:24,330 --> 00:20:24,950
Who cares?

413
00:20:25,430 --> 00:20:26,170
Money is money.

414
00:20:27,550 --> 00:20:30,290
They were probably impressed by Ozzak's terrified expression.

415
00:20:30,290 --> 00:20:31,210
What expression?

416
00:20:32,650 --> 00:20:33,250
Let's go.

417
00:20:35,130 --> 00:20:36,730
Yes, yes, I know.

418
00:20:36,770 --> 00:20:38,650
And you look twenty kilos heavier again.

419
00:20:39,350 --> 00:20:40,350
Models.

420
00:20:40,640 --> 00:20:41,300
So what?

421
00:20:41,750 --> 00:20:45,480
So I'm puffy, bro has issues with flash, but we're going to Switzerland.

422
00:20:45,950 --> 00:20:47,250
Unlike some people.

423
00:20:47,650 --> 00:20:48,450
Awesome, bro.

424
00:20:49,250 --> 00:20:50,250
What about parental consent?

425
00:20:50,550 --> 00:20:52,350
You suddenly don't need that anymore?

426
00:20:53,350 --> 00:20:56,350
Fine, Ivuska, can we go to Geneva?

427
00:20:56,650 --> 00:20:57,450
You can.

428
00:20:57,950 --> 00:20:59,550
I won't stand in the way of your happiness.

429
00:20:59,650 --> 00:21:01,050
Unlike some people.

430
00:21:03,100 --> 00:21:05,180
So, bro, let's show them!

431
00:21:05,440 --> 00:21:06,780
Like the old days.

432
00:21:07,200 --> 00:21:07,760
Wait.

433
00:21:08,080 --> 00:21:08,400
What?

434
00:21:09,210 --> 00:21:10,350
You don't have a passport.

435
00:21:12,450 --> 00:21:13,760
I can travel on my ID card, right?

436
00:21:13,760 --> 00:21:15,640
You mean that six-year-expired rag?

437
00:21:15,720 --> 00:21:17,100
We wouldn't even make it to Budejovice.

438
00:21:18,650 --> 00:21:19,350
Easy, bro.

439
00:21:19,550 --> 00:21:21,730
Just smuggle me across the border in the trunk.

440
00:21:22,070 --> 00:21:24,270
Like that time we went to see Queen in Budapest.

441
00:21:25,450 --> 00:21:26,650
Times have changed.

442
00:21:27,050 --> 00:21:27,950
Exactly.

443
00:21:28,740 --> 00:21:29,640
They have bigger trunks now.

444
00:21:29,960 --> 00:21:36,340
It's broken.

445
00:21:36,750 --> 00:21:38,650
It keeps going off.

446
00:21:39,050 --> 00:21:40,250
You're talking too loud.

447
00:21:40,250 --> 00:21:40,570
What?

448
00:21:44,980 --> 00:21:46,680
You're talking too loud.

449
00:21:47,020 --> 00:21:48,900
This is a complex machine.

450
00:21:49,080 --> 00:21:51,120
It reacts to sound levels.

451
00:21:51,220 --> 00:21:52,460
It's not just any gadget, lady.

452
00:21:53,060 --> 00:21:54,360
Don't call me lady.

453
00:21:54,740 --> 00:21:56,600
You're mashing the keys too hard.

454
00:21:57,050 --> 00:21:58,540
I've explained that to you, I'm sure.

455
00:21:58,540 --> 00:21:59,180
You'll see.

456
00:22:01,050 --> 00:22:01,750
One.

457
00:22:02,790 --> 00:22:03,430
Two.

458
00:22:08,470 --> 00:22:09,070
Yes.

459
00:22:10,650 --> 00:22:26,540
Adjust the sound level limit, resolder the circuit, reverse the polarity of the determinator.

460
00:22:26,540 --> 00:22:27,560
That long?

461
00:22:29,200 --> 00:22:29,740
Five minutes?

462
00:22:31,650 --> 00:22:33,810
If I had my notebook here.

463
00:22:35,350 --> 00:22:45,150
You could bring it.

464
00:22:46,950 --> 00:22:48,650
Do whatever you want, but just get rid of it.

465
00:22:52,550 --> 00:22:54,450
Couldn't you just disconnect the ringer?

466
00:22:55,040 --> 00:22:55,780
Or something.

467
00:22:55,780 --> 00:22:58,550
Then do that!

468
00:23:07,200 --> 00:23:07,720
Goodbye.

469
00:23:09,150 --> 00:23:14,050
Funny, what you want, that's what everyone wants in the end.

470
00:23:15,750 --> 00:23:17,250
That'll be five hundred crowns.

471
00:23:25,770 --> 00:23:29,310
Uncle, you're alive, let's celebrate!

472
00:23:31,050 --> 00:23:34,670
Oh man, you have no idea how glad we are.

473
00:23:34,670 --> 00:23:35,750
To be home again.

474
00:23:36,150 --> 00:23:40,010
Wherever you've been, you said four days and you were gone a week, what happened?

475
00:23:40,010 --> 00:23:42,310
This, what a fiasco.

476
00:23:42,590 --> 00:23:44,690
And what about you, how were things here?

477
00:23:44,770 --> 00:23:45,870
What, home alone, girl?

478
00:23:46,070 --> 00:23:49,150
It was all good, just like Paris.

479
00:23:52,750 --> 00:23:54,750
Iva, I'm starving like a wolf.

480
00:23:55,350 --> 00:23:56,650
Where did you get this?

481
00:23:57,150 --> 00:23:58,850
I broke open the piggy bank.

482
00:24:00,450 --> 00:24:02,350
And here's some wine to celebrate.

483
00:24:04,350 --> 00:24:06,450
French, original.

484
00:24:07,150 --> 00:24:08,250
Where did you buy it?

485
00:24:08,780 --> 00:24:10,800
At that DVD rental place.

486
00:24:10,900 --> 00:24:12,340
They have a wine shop now too.

487
00:24:12,480 --> 00:24:12,880
I see.

488
00:24:15,070 --> 00:24:17,270
So tell me, how was Switzerland?

489
00:24:17,270 --> 00:24:20,090
Well, we never actually made it to Switzerland.

490
00:24:20,090 --> 00:24:20,750
How come?

491
00:24:20,750 --> 00:24:26,750
All through Germany, no problem, then Ozzak climbs into the trunk before the Swiss border.

492
00:24:27,250 --> 00:24:31,610
We're pulling up, the border guard waves us through, all normal.

493
00:24:31,950 --> 00:24:32,850
But?

494
00:24:32,850 --> 00:24:33,950
But.

495
00:24:34,150 --> 00:24:45,250
Then someone floored it, couldn't brake, crashed into a parked car, the alarm went off, Ozzak started barking in the trunk, the customs officers came, drew pepper spray and weapons.

496
00:24:45,350 --> 00:24:48,750
I still don't understand why they mind someone having an animal in the trunk.

497
00:24:49,150 --> 00:24:53,730
They locked us in a cell and refused to believe Ozzak is a decent person and not a vagabond.

498
00:24:53,730 --> 00:24:55,070
They even put cuffs on me.

499
00:24:55,450 --> 00:24:56,730
Luckily on the front paws.

500
00:24:56,730 --> 00:24:57,390
Hmm.

501
00:24:57,850 --> 00:25:00,530
The agency, they apparently came through, so...

502
00:25:00,530 --> 00:25:01,550
So they rescued you?

503
00:25:02,350 --> 00:25:10,090
Actually yeah, they came, got us out of the cell, then pulled out pepper spray, took photos and that was it.

504
00:25:10,250 --> 00:25:14,350
The entire fee went to fines, the stay in the cell, and eye drops.

505
00:25:14,630 --> 00:25:16,920
What about the photos, when will we see them?

506
00:25:16,920 --> 00:25:20,120
Luckily never, the campaign will only be in Switzerland.

507
00:25:20,250 --> 00:25:22,340
I still think the Indians are right.

508
00:25:22,550 --> 00:25:23,950
Photos steal souls.

509
00:25:25,250 --> 00:25:26,350
Or was it the other way around?

510
00:25:26,750 --> 00:25:29,450
Photos are right, Indians steal souls, yeah.

511
00:25:31,150 --> 00:25:32,350
Indians steal photos.

512
00:25:34,250 --> 00:25:38,680
I think some photos should never be made public.

513
00:25:38,680 --> 00:25:39,040
Yeah.

514
00:25:40,350 --> 00:25:41,710
Everyone has a right to secrets.

515
00:25:41,950 --> 00:25:43,210
Even models.

516
00:25:43,550 --> 00:25:44,250
You're right, Dad.

517
00:25:44,650 --> 00:25:45,850
As always.

